\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{Tip_surf_schem}

\end_inset 


\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The program itself is designed to calculate the interactions in systems
 similar to that shown in fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Tip_surf_schem}

\end_inset 

, with an atomistic nano-tip embedded in a conducting macroscopic sphere
 interacting with an atomistic cluster on top of a metal substrate.
 This represents a very common experimental setup in modern AFM experiments
 using conducting tips to image thin insulating films on top of metal substrates.
 However, the code is very flexible in the types of setup it can study.
 The properties of insulating tips can be easily investigated by removing
 the conducting sphere from the system, and in fact the properties of thin
 films alone can be studied by removing the tip completely from the system.
 Some example input files at the end of this manual show the variety of
 different setups that can be studied.
 
\layout Standard

The code has the facility to perform many different types of calculations
 on a tip-surface set up.
 The program can either be used to find the minimum energy configuation
 of a given system using powerful minimisation algorithms, or perform a
 finite temperature Molecular Dynamics (MD) simulation in a number of different
 ensembles.
 To facilitate the simulation of both contact and Non-contact mode AFM,
 the tip can be moved - either between successive energy minimisations or
 during a MD run.
 
\layout Standard

Microscopic systems can be composed of a variety of different classical
 potentials and the program has the facility to implement atomic polarisation
 via the shell model, where pairwise interactions are modeled by a series
 of Buckingham style potentials.
 The modeling of covailent crystals and organic molecules is possible by
 the use of many-body potentials which comprise of bond, angle, torsion
 and out-of-plane interactions.
 
\layout Standard

The code has been designed to run efficiently on both serial and distributed
 memory multi-processor machines with Fortran 77 or 90 compilers.
 In parallel the program uses the Message Passing Interface (MPI) set of
 communication routines and is parallised according to the distributed memory
 paradgm with atomic pair decomposition.
 
\layout Section

Theoretical Model
\layout Subsection

Electrostatic energy of a system of metals and charges
\layout Standard

Consider a set of 
\emph on 
finite
\emph default 
 metallic conductors of arbitrary shape and an arbitrary distribution of
 point charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ q_{i}\}$
\end_inset 

 at the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{r}_{i}\}$
\end_inset 

 anywhere in the free space outside the conductors.
 We assume that the conductors which will hereafter be designated by indices
 
\begin_inset Formula $m,m^{\prime}$
\end_inset 

 are kept at some 
\emph on 
fixed
\emph default 
 potentials 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{m}$
\end_inset 

.
 These potentials are provided by the batteries.
 
\layout Standard

It is known from the standard textbooks (see e.g.
 Refs.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Stratton}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Landau-8}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Jackson}

\end_inset 

) how to calculate the energy accumulated in the electrostatic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset 

 created by point charges and metals.
 Using the total energy of the field, 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\frac{1}{8\pi}\int_{V}\mathbf{E}^{2}d\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset 

 (the integral is taken over the volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset 

 outside the metals since inside those the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}=0$
\end_inset 

) and applying the Poisson equation for the field, one gets:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i}\, q_{i}\phi(\mathbf{r}_{i})+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{m}\, Q_{m}\phi_{m}\label{2}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where the first sum is taken over all point charges whereas the second
 one over all conductors.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{m}=-\frac{1}{4\pi}\int\int_{S_{m}}\,\frac{\partial\phi}{\partial n}ds$
\end_inset 

 is the charge on the metal 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset 

, where the integral is performed over the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{m}$
\end_inset 

 of the metal.
 Note that the surface integral over a remote surface at infinity (which
 is surrounding all the metals and the point charges) vanishes due to rapid
 decrease of the potential to zero there 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Landau-8}

\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, this derivation is not valid for infinite metals for which this
 assumption is not correct (e.g.
 a charged infinite metal conductor).
 We also note in passing that according to classical theory, the charge
 is distributed at the surface, i.e.
 it does not penetrate into the bulk of the metal; quantum theory 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Finnis-1}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Finnis-2}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Garcia-Bagus}

\end_inset 

 gives a certain distribution of the surface charge in the direction to
 the bulk.
 
\layout Standard

The result of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{2}

\end_inset 

) has a very simple physical meaning: every charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{q}$
\end_inset 

 (either a point charge outside the metals or the distributed charge on
 a metal surface) gets energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}q\phi(\mathbf{r}_{q})$
\end_inset 

 where the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset 

 is needed to avoid double counting.
 Note that the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

 is produced both by the metals (i.e.
 by the distributed charges on their surfaces) and by the point charges.
 Note also that both the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{r}_{i})$
\end_inset 

 on point charges and the charges 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{m}$
\end_inset 

 on the metals are unknown and should be calculated by solving the Poisson
 equation.
 The effect of the metals comes into play via the boundary conditions and
 the charges 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{m}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

In order to calculate the electrostatic force imposed on any of the conductors,
 we use the method essentially similar to the one of Ref.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Landau-8}

\end_inset 

 where an arbitrary distribution of metals is considered without point charges.
 The force is obtained by differentiating the energy with respect to the
 corresponding position of the metal of interest.
 It is shown in Ref.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Landau-8}

\end_inset 

 that the same expression for the force is obtained in the cases of fixed
 potentials or fixed charges on the metals.
 This, however, is not the case if the point charges are present.
 Indeed, let us move some metal by the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset 

.
 The work 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta A=-\mathbf{F}\delta\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset 

 is done by the external force against the force 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset 

 imposed on the conductor.
 When the conductor is moved to the new position, the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

 in the system will change by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

.
 The potential on any metal 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset 

 will no longer be equal to the fixed value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{m}$
\end_inset 

 so that there should be some charge flow between the connected conductors
 to maintain the potential on them.
 Therefore, some work 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta A$
\end_inset 

 will be spent in changing the potential energy of the field (given by Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{2}

\end_inset 

)) by the amount 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta U=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i}\, q_{i}\delta\phi(\mathbf{r}_{i})+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{m}\,\phi_{m}\delta Q_{m}\]

\end_inset 

and some work 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta A_{b}$
\end_inset 

 is done in transfering charge 
\emph on 
between 
\emph default 
the conductors.
 The latter work 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta A_{b}$
\end_inset 

 is done by the batteries (as the charge flows via the battery from one
 conductor to another) and so should be taken with the minus sign: 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta A=-\delta A_{b}+\delta U$
\end_inset 

.
 Alternatively, one could think of the batteries being incorporated into
 the system; in that case it would mean that the work done by the batteries
 would reduce the total potential energy of the whole system.
 
\layout Standard

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta Q_{m}$
\end_inset 

 be the change of the charge on the conductor 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset 

 in the discussing process.
 Then the work 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta A_{b}=\sum_{m}\phi_{m}\delta Q_{m}$
\end_inset 

 (cf.
 Eq.
 (2.5) in Ref.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Landau-8}

\end_inset 

).
 Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{m}\delta Q_{m}=0$
\end_inset 

, this is the work needed to distribute the zero charge initially stored
 at infinity (where the potential is zero) between different metals by transferr
ing the amounts 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta Q_{m}$
\end_inset 

 to the each metal 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset 

.
 Using the above given expressions, we obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta A\equiv-\mathbf{F}\delta\mathbf{r}=-\sum_{m}\phi_{m}\delta Q_{m}+\delta U\]

\end_inset 

so that the final expression for the force imposed on the displaced metal
 becomes
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}=-\frac{\partial U^{eff}}{\partial\mathbf{r}}\label{force}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

with the 
\emph on 
effective energy 
\emph default 
(or the total potential energy of the whole system which includes the batteries
 as well) defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U^{eff}=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i}\, q_{i}\phi(\mathbf{r}_{i})-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{m}\, Q_{m}\phi_{m}\label{eff-energy}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Subsection

Tip-surface Interaction
\layout Standard

In order to calculate the force imposed on the tip we used the following
 expression for the total energy of the system: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{ij}\,^{\prime}v_{ij}+U_{vdW}+U_{el}\label{1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{ij}$
\end_inset 

 is the interatomic potential between atoms 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset 

.
 This interaction energy is a function of both the tip position 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

 and the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{i}$
\end_inset 

 of all atoms (and shells) involved.
 The energy 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{vdW}$
\end_inset 

 represents the van der Waals interaction between the macroscopic tip and
 substrate and depends only on the tip height 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

 with respect to the substrate (see Fig.
 1).
 Note that in the present model the macroscopic van der Waals interaction
 does not effect atomic positions.
\layout Standard

The last term in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{1}

\end_inset 

) represents the total electrostatic energy of the whole system.
 We assume that the Coulomb and covalent interactions between all atoms
 is included in the first term in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{1}

\end_inset 

) and hence should be excluded from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{el}$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{el}$
\end_inset 

 includes the interaction of the atoms in the system with the macroscopic
 tip and substrate.
 As has been demonstrated, the correct electrostatic energy should incorporate
 the work done by the battery to maintain the constant potential on the
 electrodes.
 It can be written in the following form: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U_{el}=-\frac{1}{2}Q^{(0)}V+\sum_{i}q_{i}\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r}_{i})+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j}q_{i}q_{j}\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r}_{i},\mathbf{r}_{j})\label{el-energy}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset 

 is the potential difference applied to the metal electrodes.
 Without loss of generality, one can choose the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

 on the metal plane to be zero, so that the potential on the macroscopic
 part of the tip will be 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=V$
\end_inset 

.
 We also note that the substrate is considered in the limit of a sphere
 of a very big radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\prime}\gg R$
\end_inset 

 since the metal electrodes formally cannot be infinite.
 The charge on the tip 
\emph on 
without 
\emph default 
charges outside the metals (i.e.
 when there are only bare electrodes and the polarization effects can be
 neglected) is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{(0)}$
\end_inset 

 and the electrostatic potential of the bare electrodes anywhere outside
 the metals is 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

.
 The charge 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{(0)}$
\end_inset 

 and the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

 depend only on the geometry of the capacitor formed by the two electrodes
 and on the bias 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset 

.
 The charge 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{(0)}$
\end_inset 

 can be calculated from the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

 as follows 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Landau-8}

\end_inset 

: 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{(0)}=-\frac{1}{4\pi}\int\int\,\frac{\partial\phi^{(0)}}{\partial n}ds$
\end_inset 

 where the integration is performed over the entire surface of the macroscopic
 part of the tip with the integrand being the normal derivative of the potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

; the normal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset 

 is directed outside the metal.
 Summation in the second term of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{el-energy}

\end_inset 

) is performed over the atoms and shells of the sample and those of the
 tip apex which are represented by point charges 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset 

 at positions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{i}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}^{\prime})$
\end_inset 

 in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{el-energy}

\end_inset 

) is the potential at 
\emph on 

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset 


\emph default 
 due to image charges
\emph on 
 induced 
\emph default 
on all the metals by a unit point charge at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}^{\prime}$
\end_inset 

.
 This function is directly related to the Green function 
\series bold 

\begin_inset Formula $G(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}^{\prime})$
\end_inset 


\series default 
 of the Laplace equation, 
\series bold 

\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}^{\prime})=G(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}^{\prime})-\frac{1}{\mid\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\mid}$
\end_inset 


\series default 
, and is symmetric, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}^{\prime})=\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime},\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

, due to the symmetry of the Green function itself 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Jackson}

\end_inset 

.
 The total potential at
\series bold 
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset 


\series default 
 due to a net charge induced on all conductors present in the system by
 all the point charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ q_{i}\}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r})=\sum_{i}q_{i}\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}_{i})\label{fi-ind-nwe}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 is the 
\emph on 
image potential
\emph default 
.
 Note that the last double summation in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{el-energy}

\end_inset 

) includes the 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset 

 term as well.
 This term corresponds to the interaction of the charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset 

 with its own polarization (similar to the polaronic effect in solid-state
 physics).
 
\layout Standard

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}^{\prime})$
\end_inset 

 and, therefore, the image potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

, together with the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

 of the bare electrodes could be calculated if we knew the exact Green function
 of the electrostatic problem 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta_{\mathbf{r}^{\prime}}G(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}^{\prime})=-4\pi\delta(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\label{Poisson}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

with the corresponding boundary conditions (
\begin_inset Formula $G(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}^{\prime})=0$
\end_inset 

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}^{\prime}$
\end_inset 

 belong to either the substrate or the tip surface) 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Jackson}

\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, given the applied bias 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset 

, the geometric characteristics of the capacitor and the positions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{r}_{j}\}$
\end_inset 

 of the point charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ q_{i}\}$
\end_inset 

 between the tip and sample, one can calculate the electrostatic energy
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{el}$
\end_inset 

.
 The problem is that the Green function for real tip-sample shapes and arrangeme
nts is difficult to calculate.
 In this study we use the planar-spherical geometry of the junction as depicted
 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Tip_surf_schem}

\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Subsection


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{charges_sol}

\end_inset 

Solution of the electrostatic problem of point charges inside the sphere-plane
 capacitor
\layout Standard

First, let us consider the calculation of the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

 of the bare electrodes, i.e.
 the capacitor problem.
 We note that the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

 satisfies the same boundary conditions as the original problem, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}=V$
\end_inset 

 at the lower and upper electrodes, respectively.
 The solution for the plane-spherical capacitor is well known 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Smythe}

\end_inset 

 and can be given using the method of image charges.
 Since we will need this solution for calculating forces later on, we have
 to give it here in detail.
 It is convenient to choose the coordinate system as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Tip_surf_schem}

\end_inset 

.
 Then it is easy to check that the following two 
\emph on 
infinite 
\emph default 
sequences of image charges give the potential at the sphere and the metal
 plane as 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset 

 and zero respectively.
 The first sequence is given by the image charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma_{1}=RV$
\end_inset 

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma_{k+1}=\frac{\varsigma_{k}}{D_{k}}$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall k=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset 

, where the dimensionless constants 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}$
\end_inset 

 are defined by the recurrence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k+1}=2\lambda-\frac{1}{D_{k}}$
\end_inset 

with 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}=2\lambda$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\frac{z_{s}}{R}>1$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

 being the distance between the sphere centre and the plane (Fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Tip_surf_schem}

\end_inset 

).
 The point charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varsigma_{k}\}$
\end_inset 

 are all inside the sphere along the normal line passing through the sphere
 centre.
 Their 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

-coordinates are as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}=z_{s}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{k+1}=R\left(\lambda-\frac{1}{D_{k}}\right)=R(D_{k+1}-\lambda)$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall k=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset 

.
 The second sequence of charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varsigma_{k}^{\prime}\}$
\end_inset 

 is formed by the images of the first sequence with respect to the metal
 plane, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma_{k}^{\prime}=-\varsigma_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{k}^{\prime}=-z_{k}$
\end_inset 

.
 An interesting point about the image charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varsigma_{k}\}$
\end_inset 

 is that they converge very quickly at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{\infty}=R\sqrt{\lambda^{2}-1}$
\end_inset 

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{k}\rightarrow z_{\infty}$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset 

) and that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{k+1}<z_{k}$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall k$
\end_inset 

.
 This is because the numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}$
\end_inset 

 converge rapidly to the limiting value 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\infty}=\lambda+\sqrt{\lambda^{2}-1}$
\end_inset 

 which follows from the original recurrent relation above, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\infty}=2\lambda-\frac{1}{D_{\infty}}$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, while calculating the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

, one can consider the charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varsigma_{k}\}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varsigma_{k}^{\prime}\}$
\end_inset 

 explicitly only up to some 
\begin_inset Formula $k=k_{0}-1$
\end_inset 

 and then sum up the rest of the charges to infinity analytically to obtain
 the effective charge 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma_{\infty}=\sum_{k=k_{0}}^{\infty}\varsigma_{k}=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\varsigma_{k_{0}}}{D_{\infty}^{n}}=\frac{\varsigma_{k_{0}}D_{\infty}}{D_{\infty}-1}$
\end_inset 

 to be placed at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{\infty}$
\end_inset 

.
 This can be used 
\emph on 
instead 
\emph default 
of the rest of the series: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})=\sum_{k=1}^{k_{0}}\overline{\varsigma}_{k}\left(\frac{1}{|\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}_{\varsigma_{k}}|}-\frac{1}{|\mathbf{r}-\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{\varsigma_{k}}|}\right)\label{fi-0}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varsigma}_{k}=\varsigma_{k}$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k<k_{0}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varsigma}_{k_{0}}=\varsigma_{\infty}$
\end_inset 

; then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{\varsigma_{k}}=(0,0,z_{k})$
\end_inset 

 is the position vector of the charge 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{\varsigma_{k}^{\prime}}=\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{\varsigma_{k}}=(0,0,-z_{k})$
\end_inset 

 is the position of the charge 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma_{k}^{\prime}$
\end_inset 

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\sigma}$
\end_inset 

 means reflection with respect to the substrate surface 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset 

).
 To find the charge 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{(0)}$
\end_inset 

 which is also needed for the calculation of the electrostatic energy, Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{el-energy}

\end_inset 

), one should calculate the normal derivative of the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

 on the sphere and then take the corresponding surface integral (see above).
 However, it is useful to recall that the total charge induced on the metal
 sphere due to an external charge is equal exactly to the image charge inside
 the sphere 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Landau-8}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Jackson}

\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, one immediately obtains: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
Q^{(0)}=\sum_{k=1}^{k_{0}}\overline{\varsigma}_{k}\label{Q_0}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Note that the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

 and the charge 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{(0)}$
\end_inset 

 depend on the position 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

 of the sphere 
\emph on 
indirectly 
\emph default 
via the charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and their positions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{\varsigma_{k}}$
\end_inset 

 according to the recurrent expressions above.
 Therefore, one has to be careful when calculating the contribution to the
 force imposed on the tip due to bias V (i.e.
 when differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(0)}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{(0)}$
\end_inset 

 in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{el-energy}

\end_inset 

)).
 
\layout Standard

Now we turn to the calculation of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}^{\prime})$
\end_inset 

 in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{el-energy}

\end_inset 

).
 This function corresponds to the image potential at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset 

 due to a unit charge at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}^{\prime}$
\end_inset 

.
 This potential is to be defined in such a way that together with the direct
 potential of the unit point charge, it should be zero on both electrodes
 (the boundary condition for the Green function).
 Thus, let us consider a unit charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1$
\end_inset 

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{q}$
\end_inset 

 somewhere outside the metal electrodes as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{2spheres}

\end_inset 

.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
collapsed false

\layout Standard
\align center 

\begin_inset Graphics
	filename xfig.image.eps
	display monochrome
	width 10cm

\end_inset 


\layout Caption

Construction of image charges in the sphere-plane capacitor system due to
 one charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

 outside the metals.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{2spheres}

\end_inset 


\end_inset 

  We first create the direct image 
\begin_inset Formula $-q$
\end_inset 

 of this charge with respect to the plane at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{q}^{\prime}=\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{q}$
\end_inset 

 to maintain zero potential at the plane.
 Then, we create images of the two charges, 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-q=-1$
\end_inset 

, with respect to the sphere to get two image charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{1}=-\frac{R}{|\mathbf{r}_{q}-\mathbf{R}_{s}|}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{1}=\frac{R}{|\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{q}-\mathbf{R}_{s}|}$
\end_inset 

, as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{2spheres}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}_{s}=(0,0,z_{s})$
\end_inset 

.
 These image charges are both inside the sphere by construction and their
 positions can be written down using a vector function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{r})=\mathbf{R}_{s}+R^{2}\frac{\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{R}_{s}}{|\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{R}_{s}|^{2}}$
\end_inset 

 as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{\xi_{1}}=\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{r}_{q})$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{\zeta_{1}}=\mathbf{f}(\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{q})$
\end_inset 

.
 Now the potential at the surface will be zero.
 At the next step we construct the images 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{1}^{\prime}=-\xi_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{1}^{\prime}=-\zeta_{1}$
\end_inset 

 of the charges 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{1}$
\end_inset 

 in the plane at points 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{\xi_{1}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{\zeta_{1}}$
\end_inset 

 respectively, to get the potential at the plane also zero.
 This process is continued and in this way two infinite sequences of image
 charges are constructed, which are given by the following recurrence relations:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
\xi_{k+1}=\xi_{k}\frac{R}{|\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{\xi_{k}}-\mathbf{R}_{s}|}\\
\mathbf{r}_{\zeta_{k+1}}=\mathbf{f}(\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{\xi_{k}})=\mathbf{R}_{s}+R^{2}\frac{\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{\xi_{k}}-\mathbf{R}_{s}}{|\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{\xi_{k}}-\mathbf{R}_{s}|^{2}}\end{array}\right.\label{1st-seq}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset 

 and similarly for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset 

-sequence.
 Note, however, that the two sequences start from different initial charges.
 Namely, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset 

-sequence starts from the original charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

 while the 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset 

-sequence from its image in the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $-q$
\end_inset 

.
 The two sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\xi_{k}\}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\zeta_{k}\}$
\end_inset 

 are to be accompanied by the other two sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\xi_{k}^{\prime}\}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\zeta_{k}^{\prime}\}$
\end_inset 

 which are the images of the former charges with respect to the plane.
 The four sequences of the image charges and the charges 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-q$
\end_inset 

 provide the correct solution for the problem formulated above since they
 produce the potential which is the solution of the corresponding Poisson
 equation and, at the same time, is zero both on the metal sphere and the
 metal plane.
 
\layout Standard

It is useful to study the convergence properties of the sequences of image
 charges.
 To simplify the notations, let us assume that the original charge is in
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $xz$
\end_inset 

-plane.
 Then it follows from Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{1st-seq}

\end_inset 

) that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\xi_{k+1}}<x_{\xi_{k}}$
\end_inset 

 .
 It is also seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\xi_{k}}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{\xi_{k}}\rightarrow z_{\infty}=R\sqrt{\lambda^{2}-1}$
\end_inset 

 (see above) as 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset 

 and the same for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset 

-sequence.
 This means that the image charges inside the sphere move towards the vertical
 line passing through the centre of the sphere and finally converge at the
 same point 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{\infty}$
\end_inset 

.
 This is the same behaviour we observed for charges in the capacitor problem
 at the beginning of this subsection (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{2spheres}

\end_inset 

).
 In fact, the calculation clearly shows a very fast convergence so that
 we can again sum up the series of charges from some 
\begin_inset Formula $k=k_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
 Thus, the image potential at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset 

 due to the unit charge at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{q}$
\end_inset 

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}_{q})=-\frac{1}{\mathbf{r}-\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{q}}+\sum_{k=1}^{k_{0}}\left[\overline{\xi}_{k}\left(\frac{1}{|\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}_{\xi_{k}}|}-\frac{1}{|\mathbf{r}-\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{\xi_{k}}|}\right)+\overline{\zeta}_{k}\left(\frac{1}{|\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}_{\zeta_{k}}|}-\frac{1}{|\mathbf{r}-\widehat{\sigma}\mathbf{r}_{\zeta_{k}}|}\right)\right]\label{Fi-ind}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\xi}_{k}=\xi_{k}$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k<k_{0}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\xi}_{k_{0}}=\xi_{\infty}=\xi_{k_{0}}\frac{D_{\infty}}{D_{\infty}-1}$
\end_inset 

, and similarly for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset 

-sequence.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\infty}$
\end_inset 

 is the geometrical characteristic of the capacitor introduced at the beginning
 of this subsection.
 
\layout Standard

As it has been already mentioned in Section 2.1, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}_{q})$
\end_inset 

 must be symmetric with respect to the permutation of its two variables.
 It is not at all obvious that this is the case since the meaning of its
 two arguments in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Fi-ind}

\end_inset 

) is rather different.
 Nevertheless, we show in ref.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{our_imageforce}

\end_inset 

 that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ind}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}_{q})$
\end_inset 

 is symmetric.
\layout Subsection

The calculation of the total force acting on the tip
\layout Standard

In order to calculate the total force acting on the tip, one has to differentiat
e the total energy, Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{1}

\end_inset 

), with respect to the position of the sphere, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}_{s}$
\end_inset 

.
 Since we are interested only in the force acting in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

-direction, it is sufficient to study the dependence of the energy on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

.
 There will be three contributions to the force.
 The second contribution to the force comes from the van der Waals interaction
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{French}

\end_inset 

.
 Finally, the interatomic interactions lead to a force which is calculated
 by differentiating the shell-model energy (the first term in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{1}

\end_inset 

)).
 Therefore, 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{tip}=-\frac{dU_{sh}}{dz_{s}}-\frac{dU_{vdW}}{dz_{s}}-\frac{dU_{el}}{dz_{s}}\label{force-1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{sh}=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{ij}\,^{\prime}v_{ij}$
\end_inset 

 is the shell model energy.
 We recall that the summation here is performed over all atoms in regions
 1 to 4.
 Only positions of the atoms in region 1 depend directly on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

 since atoms in other regions are allowed to relax.
 However, their equilibrium positions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{i}^{(0)}$
\end_inset 

, determined by the minimisation of the energy of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{1}

\end_inset 

), will depend 
\emph on 
indirectly
\emph default 
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

 at equilibrium, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{i}^{(0)}=\mathbf{r}_{i}^{(0)}(z_{s})$
\end_inset 

.
 Then, we also recall that the electrostatic energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{el}$
\end_inset 

, depends only on positions of atoms, as well as on the tip position 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Let us denote the positions of atoms by a vector 
\series bold 

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=(\mathbf{r}_{1},\mathbf{r}_{2},\ldots)$
\end_inset 


\series default 
.
 The total energy 
\begin_inset Formula $U=U(\mathbf{x},z_{s})$
\end_inset 

, where the direct dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

 comes from relaxed tip atoms of the shell model energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{sh}$
\end_inset 

, and from the electrostatic energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{el}$
\end_inset 

.
 In equilibrium the total energy is a minimum:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\partial U}{\partial\mathbf{x}}\right)_{z_{s}}=0\label{equi}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where the derivatives are calculated at a given fixed tip position 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

.
 Let 
\series bold 

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{0}=(\mathbf{r}_{1}^{(0)},\mathbf{r}_{2}^{(0)},\ldots)$
\end_inset 

 
\series default 
be the solution of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{equi}

\end_inset 

).
 Then, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{0}=\mathbf{x}_{0}(z_{s})$
\end_inset 

, we have for the force: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{tip}=-\frac{dU(\mathbf{x}_{0}(z_{s}),z_{s})}{dz_{s}}=-\left(\frac{\partial U}{\partial\mathbf{x}_{0}}\right)_{z_{s}}\frac{\partial\mathbf{x}_{0}}{\partial z_{s}}-\left(\frac{\partial U}{\partial z_{s}}\right)_{\mathbf{x}_{0}}=-\left(\frac{\partial U}{\partial z_{s}}\right)_{\mathbf{x}_{0}}\label{fin-prelast}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where we have used Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{equi}

\end_inset 

).
 This result can be simplified further.
 Indeed, the partial derivative of the shell-model energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{\partial U_{sh}}{\partial z_{s}}$
\end_inset 

, is equal to the sum of all 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

-forces acting on atoms in region 1 due to all shell-model interactions,
 since only these atoms are responsible for the dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

 in the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{sh}$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, finally we have: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{tip}=\sum_{i\in1}\left(F_{iz}^{(sh)}\right)_{\mathbf{x}_{0}}-\frac{dU_{vdW}}{dz_{s}}-\left(\frac{\partial U_{el}}{\partial z_{s}}\right)_{\mathbf{x}_{0}}\label{fin-force}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where the first summation runs only over fixed tip atoms.
 Thus, in order to calculate the force imposed on the tip at a given tip
 position 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

, one has to relax the positions of atoms using the
\emph on 
 total energy 
\emph default 
of the system, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{sh}+U_{el}$
\end_inset 

.
 Then calculate the shell-model force, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{iz}^{(sh)}$
\end_inset 

, acting on every fixed tip atom in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

-direction as well as the electrostatic contribution to the force given
 by the last term in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fin-force}

\end_inset 

).
 The van der Waals force between macroscopic tip and sample does not depend
 on the geometry of atoms and can be calculated just once for every given
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{s}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Subsubsection

Definition of the Instantaineous Force on the Tip (for MD)
\layout Standard


\series medium 
In the case where the system is dynamic and atoms are given kinetic energy,
 it becomes obvious that th
\series default 
e
\series medium 
 definition
\series default 
 of the tip force given in the previous section
\series medium 
 no longer holds, since the forces on free atoms are no longer zero
\series default 
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial U}{\partial\mathbf{r}}\neq0$
\end_inset 

.

\series medium 
 It is also 
\series default 
clear that because of this
\series medium 
 when the entire tip is far from the surface, region 1 will experience large
 fluctuations in force 
\series default 
of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fin-prelast}

\end_inset 

) due to oscillating other tip atoms belonging to the adjacent region 2.
 Moreover, these fluctuations will not decay with the distance from the
 surface which is in clear contradiction with what one would expect from
 the tip force which is physically due to the interaction with the surface
\series medium 
.
 
\series default 
Even for a completely isolated tip the force fluctuations are large although,
 since region 2 atoms vibrate around equilibrium positions, the average
 force fluctuates around zero value.
 Hence, we conclude that the final form of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fin-prelast}

\end_inset 

) can only be used for calculating the force in mechanical equilibrium or
 when calculating the 
\emph on 
average
\emph default 
 force during MD simulations.
 If we are interested in the actual 
\emph on 
fluctuations
\emph default 
 of the tip force for any given tip position 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

, Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fin-prelast}

\end_inset 

) cannot be applied.
 
\layout Standard

What is needed i
\series medium 
n order to provide an alternative 
\series default 
expression for the tip force
\series medium 
 
\series default 
which would work for both static and dynamic situations, is the definition
 of an
\series medium 
 
\series default 
\emph on 
instantaneous 
\series medium 
\emph default 
force 
\series default 
for arbitrary positions of atoms in the junction.
 At first, one might be tempted to define the tip force as the partial derivativ
e, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{\partial U}{\partial Q}$
\end_inset 

, of the total system energy 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset 

 with respect to tip height 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

 at 
\emph on 
arbitrary
\emph default 
 positions of atoms, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset 

, which are allowed to relax
\series medium 
.
 
\series default 
However, this definition, as can easily be seen, leads to the same expression
 for the force, Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fin-prelast}

\end_inset 

), because only atoms in region 1 depend explicitly on 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

, and thus cannot be accepted.
\layout Standard

In order to obtain an appropriate definition of the tip force, we invoke
 a general non-equilibrium microscopic consideration in which the total
 Hamiltonian of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

tip - surface
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 system was shown 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{KANT_QM_coarse-grained}

\end_inset 

 to be split as follows:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H=H_{s}+\Phi+H_{T}\label{Hamiltonian}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Here
\series medium 
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{s}$
\end_inset 

 is the
\series default 
 sum of the independent
\series medium 
 
\series default 
\emph on 
microscopic
\emph default 
 
\series medium 
Hamiltonian
\series default 
s
\series medium 
 of the 
\series default 
isolated 
\series medium 
surface
\series default 
 and the isolated tip.
 Either of those contains kinetic and potential energies of the constituent
 atoms.
 Note that atomic positions in the tip part of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{s}$
\end_inset 

 are defined 
\emph on 
relatively
\emph default 
 to the fixed part of the tip (e.g.
 using internal coordinates).
 Note also that there is 
\emph on 
no
\emph default 
 interaction between atoms in the surface and in the tip included in 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{s}$
\end_inset 

.
 This interaction is completely included in the second term, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset 

, in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Hamiltonian}

\end_inset 

).
 Since absolute positions of the tip atoms are to be used while specifying
 the tip-surface interaction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset 

 depends both on the atomic positions and the tip height, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

.
 As the distance between the tip and surface increases, the tip-surface
 interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset 

 tends to zero.
 Finally,
\series medium 
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{T}$
\end_inset 

 
\series default 
is the 
\emph on 
macroscopic 
\series medium 
\emph default 
Hamiltonian of the tip 
\series default 
which contains kinetic and elastic energy of the cantilever as well as
\series medium 
 
\series default 
the excitation term
\series medium 
.
 
\series default 
It depends exclusively on 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

 and also contributes to the conservative part of the tip force.
 Since we are not interested in the conservative contribution (it does not
 contribute to the force fluctuations), it will be ignored in this presentation.
 Note that the interaction term, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset 

 can always be defined for arbitrary complex many body interactions between
 the tip and surface, and thus our treatment is not limited to systems consistin
g only of pairwise interactions.
 
\layout Standard

It then follows from the microscopic non-equilibrium theory that the instantaneo
us microscopic force acting on the tip (which completely includes the 
\emph on 
stochastic
\emph default 
 contribution due to atomic vibrations 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{NC-AFM_book_my-contribution}

\end_inset 

) should be defined as follows: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F=-\frac{\partial\Phi}{\partial Q}=f_{13}+f_{23}\label{force-correct-1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\series medium 

\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}$
\end_inset 

 
\series default 
is
\series medium 
 the sum of the 
\series default 
vertical 
\series medium 
forces acting on all the atoms in region 
\series default 

\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 


\series medium 
 due to all of the atoms in region 
\series default 

\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{tip-force-def-Tom}

\end_inset 

.
 The important difference with the static definition of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fin-prelast}

\end_inset 

) is that the force is defined as the partial derivative of the
\emph on 
 interaction
\emph default 
 energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset 

 rather than the 
\emph on 
total 
\emph default 
energy 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset 

.
 W
\series medium 
e 
\series default 
see
\series medium 
 that the
\series default 
 microscopic
\series medium 
 force on the tip 
\series default 
is given as
\series medium 
 the 
\series default 
sum of the 
\emph on 
partial forces
\series medium 
\emph default 
 on 
\series default 
\emph on 
all
\series medium 
\emph default 
 atoms of the tip due to all of the atoms in the surface
\series default 
.
 
\layout Standard


\series medium 
The above expression does not require that the system is in equilibrium,
 and
\series default 
, due to partitioning of the total Hamiltonian discussed above, Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Hamiltonian}

\end_inset 

), it naturally tends to zero when the tip and the surface are separated.
 It
\series medium 
 is also equivalent to the 
\series default 
static
\series medium 
 definition 
\series default 
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fin-prelast}

\end_inset 

) 
\series medium 
if the system is in equilibrium.
 
\series default 
Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{21}=-f_{12}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{22}=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{11}=0$
\end_inset 

 at any given time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

, we can also write 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset 

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F=\left(f_{23}+f_{22}+f_{21}\right)+\left(f_{13}+f_{12}+f_{11}\right)\label{final-force}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The first term (all three terms in the first brackets) is equal to the sum
 of the total forces acting on atoms in region 2 due to all other atoms
 in the system; it is equal to zero in mechanical equilibrium.
 Thus, in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset 

 reduces to the second term (the second brackets) which is equal to the
 sum of forces acting on the frozen atoms of the tip comprising region 3
 which is indeed identical to that given by Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fin-prelast}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

In practical calculations the expression for the force (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{force-correct-1}

\end_inset 

) is not very convenient since it requires calculation of
\series medium 
 
\series default 
partial forces
\series medium 
 due to different regions to be recorded during 
\series default 
each simulation step
\series medium 
.
 
\series default 
The equivalent expression (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{final-force}

\end_inset 

), which will be referred to as the 
\emph on 
dynamic
\emph default 
 definition of the tip force (as opposed to the 
\emph on 
static
\emph default 
 definition of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fin-prelast}

\end_inset 

)) is much more convenient since it contains the sum of total forces acting
 on 
\emph on 
all
\emph default 
 atoms of the tip.
 This expresion is used in the code when calculating the continuous force
 on the tip during a simulaion.
 
\layout Subsection

Interatomic Potentials
\layout Subsubsection

Force Field
\layout Standard

The potential energy surface of the system is modelled by the following
 force field:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
E=\sum_{b}^{N_{b}}K_{b}(b-b_{0})^{2}+\sum_{\theta}^{N_{\theta}}K_{\theta}(\theta-\theta_{0})^{2}+\sum_{\phi}^{N_{\phi}}K_{\phi}\left[1+\cos(n\phi-\phi_{0})\right]+\sum_{\chi}^{N_{\chi}}K_{\chi}\left[1+\cos(n\chi-\chi_{0})\right]\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
+\sum_{ij}\frac{q_{i}q_{j}}{\varepsilon r_{ij}}+\sum_{ij}C_{ij}r_{ij}^{-n_{ij}}+\sum_{ij}A_{ij}e^{-\frac{r_{ij}}{\rho_{ij}}}\label{force-field}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The first four terms in the above expression apply to the many body interactions
 in the system and summations only apply to the specified interactions,
 with the parameters suplied by the user and the values of the internal
 coordinates (bond lengths 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

, angles between bonds 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset 

, torsions about bonds 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

 and out-of-plane angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset 

) calculated using the expressions in section 2.5.2.
 Many body interactions are used to model covalently bonded crystals and
 organic molecules in the system.
 
\layout Standard

The final three terms in the above expression are pairwise interactions,
 and are summed over all pairs of atoms in the system (except those exluded
 in covalent bond or angle interactions).
 The program implements the Shell Model to calculate pairwise interactions,
 first introduced in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{shell-dick}

\end_inset 

.
 In this scheme, atoms are represented by positively charged cores connected
 to negatively charged shells by harmonic springs, which represent nuclear
 and electron charge respectively.
 The equilibrium distance between the core and shell is a representation
 of the electronic polarization of that atom.
 Cores and shells of the same atom only interact via the harmonic spring,
 however each atomic core and shell interacts via colombic forces with all
 other cores and shells in the system.
 
\layout Standard

Short range repulsive and Van de Waals forces are descibed by pairwise Buckingha
m potentials (last two terms in the above expression), which act only between
 shells.
 
\layout Subsubsection

Internal Coordinates
\layout Standard

The internal coordinates used to calculate the energy expressions for many
 body intercations are described below.
 The internal coordinates are defined between the cores, and not shells,
 of atoms.
 
\layout Standard

