\layout Caption

Routines and the corresponding files responsible for the interface dealing
 with imposed constraines.
 The last column states if any extra coding is required when an additional
 constraint is to be added.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{Table::constraines}

\end_inset 


\end_inset 

We shall first explain the main ideas of very general constraints; then
 linear constrains which are implemented in a rather general way in the
 code will be discussed specifically.
 
\layout Subsubsection

How constrains are dealt with in the code
\layout Standard

Constraints are dealt with in the following general way: every constrained
 equation specifies a single atomic coordinate of some atom (say, coordinate
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 of atom 3, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset 

) which is a function of other coordinates of the same and/or some other
 atoms, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}=\xi(y_{3},z_{1},x_{2})$
\end_inset 

.
 The coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset 

 is then made 
\emph on 
redundand
\emph default 
 and is removed from the optimisation space.
 The consequence of this is that, when calculating the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 in the optimisation space associated with other coordinates which are involved
 in the given constraint, there will be an additional contribution due to
 the constraint.
 In the example above coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{3}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset 

 are involved, so that the energy 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E=E(x_{1},y_{1},z_{1},x_{2},y_{2},z_{2},x_{3}(y_{3},z_{1},x_{2}),y_{3},z_{3})\equiv\widetilde{E}(x_{1},y_{1},z_{1},x_{2},y_{2},z_{2},y_{3},z_{3})\]

\end_inset 

 is a function of all coordinates except for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 associated with this coordinate is not needed during optimisation.
 However, e.g.
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{3}$
\end_inset 

 becomes:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\widetilde{f}_{3y}=-\frac{\partial\widetilde{E}}{\partial y_{3}}=-\frac{\partial E}{\partial y_{3}}-\frac{\partial E}{\partial x_{3}}\frac{\partial x_{3}}{\partial y_{3}}=f_{3y}+f_{3x}\frac{\partial x_{3}}{\partial y_{3}}=f_{3y}+f_{3x}\frac{\partial\xi}{\partial y_{3}}\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3y}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3x}$
\end_inset 

 are the actual (physical) forces on atom 3 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 directions, respectively.
 These are calculated routinely in the code irrespective of the constraints.
 The derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\xi}{\partial y_{3}}$
\end_inset 

 needed for the calculation of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{3y}$
\end_inset 

 should be calculated analytically for every particular constraint from
 the known function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset 

 and then coded in in the appropriate places.
 
\layout Standard

There is presently only one important limitation on the atoms involved in
 constraints: a reduntand coordinate must be contained in only one constraint;
 it is not allowed that it is a member of another constraint as well.
 However, other coordinates are allowed to participate in several constraints.
\layout Standard

A note for programmers: coordinates allowed to relax have their relaxation
 flags (
\family typewriter 
iRx
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRy
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRz
\family default 
) fixed to 1; coordinates not allowed to relax have the flags equal to 0;
 redundand coordinates, however, have their flags equal to 2.
 Gradients are calculated for all atoms which have their flags larger than
 zero.
\layout Subsubsection

Linear constraines
\layout Standard

In the case of linear constraines atomic coordinates of atoms (either different,
 the same or both) may be related linearly to each other.
 Let us collect all those related atomic Cartesian coordinates into a set
 
\begin_inset Formula $(r_{i})$
\end_inset 

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

 is not an atom number, but rather a number in the set).
 Then, the linear relationship between memebers of the set can be expressed
 as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{i}C_{i}r_{i}=0\label{Constraines-view}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset 

 are some constants defined by the nature of the specific constraint.
 Note that not all atoms and all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

 components of atomic coordinates may be present.
 In practice several equations like that given above can be supplied.
 Different constraints will be distinguished by an additional index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The simplest example is to allow atoms to move only along certain directions.
 Simply by specifying relaxation flags 
\family typewriter 
iRx
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRy
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRz
\family default 
 in the input (opposite to atomic coordinates, see section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::coord-box}

\end_inset 

) one can already allow atoms to move only along 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

 axes or in 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $yz$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $xz$
\end_inset 

 planes; additional constraines are not required in all those cases.
 However, imagine you would like to allow, say, atom 5 to move only along
 the (111) direction, i.e.
 to have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}=y_{5}=z_{5}$
\end_inset 

.
 In this case you will have to specify the following 2 constraints: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x_{5}-y_{5}=0\,\,\,\textrm{and}\,\,\, z_{5}-y_{5}=0\]

\end_inset 

Obviously, there is only one independent coordinate in this case.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}$
\end_inset 

 is considered as the redundand coordinate from the first constraint and
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{5}$
\end_inset 

 - from the second (since the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{5}$
\end_inset 

 must not be chosen as a redundand coordinate as it appears in both conditions),
 the only 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

active
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 coordinate in this case will be 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{5}$
\end_inset 

.
 In more complicated cases different atoms may be involved as well.
\layout Standard

The first coordinate in the constraints equations like Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Constraines-view}

\end_inset 

) with nonzero coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}^{(k)}\neq0$
\end_inset 

, as supplied in the input (section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::constraint-box}

\end_inset 

), is treated automatically as the redundand variable 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}^{(k)}$
\end_inset 

 for the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

.
 This allows to express the redundant variable via all others involved in
 the given constraint 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
r_{1}^{(k)}=-\sum_{i\neq1}^{(k)}\frac{C_{i}^{(k)}}{C_{1}^{(k)}}r_{i}^{(k)}\label{Constraines-view1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

and then calculate the correction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{j}^{(k)}$
\end_inset 

 to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{j}$
\end_inset 

 on any of the nonredundand atoms 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

 due to the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 as: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta_{j}^{(k)}=\frac{\partial E}{\partial r_{1}^{(k)}}\frac{\partial r_{1}^{(k)}}{\partial r_{j}}=-f_{1}^{(k)}\frac{C_{i(j)}^{(k)}}{C_{1}^{(k)}}\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $i\equiv i(j)$
\end_inset 

 is the position of atom 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

 in the list of atoms involved in the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

.
 The total 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 is obtained by adding corrections 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{j}^{(k)}$
\end_inset 

 due to all constraints to the physical force 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Subsubsection

Constant distance between two atoms
\layout Standard

Another simple (but nonlinear) constraint which has been implemented is
 to keep a distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

, between two atoms constant.
 If, say, atoms 1 and 2 are involved, then the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 component of the first atom specified in the input (section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::constraint-box}

\end_inset 

) is considered as redundant.
 It is expressed via other coordinates as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \[
x_{1}=x_{2}\pm\sqrt{d^{2}-(y_{1}-y_{2})^{2}-(z_{1}-z_{2})^{2}}\]

\end_inset 

where two choices of the sign are possible.
 The correction to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 associated with nonredundand coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{2}$
\end_inset 

 is calculated correspondingly.
\layout Subsubsection

Constant angle between three atoms
\layout Standard

If angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 between three atoms, say atoms 1, 2 and 3, is to be kept constant, then
 the redundand coordinate is choisen to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 coordinate of the first atom in the input (section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::constraint-box}

\end_inset 

).
 It is expressed via other 8 coordinates as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \[
x_{1}=x_{2}+\frac{1}{x_{32}^{2}-r_{32}^{2}\cos^{2}\alpha}\left\{ -x_{32}d\pm\sqrt{\left(x_{32}d\right)^{2}-\left(x_{32}^{2}-r_{32}^{2}\cos^{2}\alpha\right)\left(d^{2}-\Delta_{12}^{2}r_{32}^{2}\cos^{2}\alpha\right)}\right\} \]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d=y_{12}y_{32}+z_{12}z_{32}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{12}^{2}=y_{12}^{2}+z_{12}^{2}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{32}^{2}=x_{32}^{2}+y_{32}^{2}+z_{32}^{2}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{32}=x_{3}-x_{2}$
\end_inset 

 , etc.
 The correction to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

forces
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 are straighforward to calculate; they look very cumbersome and not yet
 implemented.
 
\layout Subsection

Molecular Dynamics Algorithms
\layout Standard

If a Molecular Dynamics (MD) simulation is being performed, then the trajectorie
s of atoms are integrated at each timestep using the standard Verlet Leapfrog
 algorithm 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Allen-tildesley}

\end_inset 

 in the NVE ensemble, and a variation of it if a thermostat is used to simulate
 in the NVT ensemble.
 The different algorithms used are described in the following section.
 
\layout Subsubsection

NVE Verlet Leapfrog
\layout Standard

The standard Verlet Leapfrog algorithm first generates new velocities at
 timestep 
\begin_inset Formula $n+\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset 

 from the velocities at timestep 
\begin_inset Formula $n-\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset 

 and the forces on all atoms as follows:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{v}(t+\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\leftarrow\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)+\Delta t\frac{\underline{f}(t)}{m}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Then the positions of all atoms are advanced one timestep based on the new
 velocities:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{r}(t+\Delta t)\leftarrow\underline{r}(t)+\Delta t\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The tempurature of the system at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 is then calculated as the average of the temperatures of the system at
 timestep 
\begin_inset Formula $t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\frac{1}{2}\Delta t$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The initial velocities for the system can optionally be provided by the
 user in the input file, however if they are not the program asigns randomly
 oriented velocites to each of the free atoms in the system based on the
 given system temperature, ensuring that the total translational and rotational
 angular momentum of the system is zero.
\layout Subsubsection

NVT with Gaussian Thermostat
\layout Standard

If the system is to be simulated in the NVT ensembe, then the user has the
 choice of four different algothims, the Gaussian thermostat 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{gauss-ts}

\end_inset 

, Berendsen thermostat, the Nose-Hoover thermostat 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{hoover-ts}

\end_inset 

 and stochastic boundary conditions 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{stochastic-md}

\end_inset 

.
 The first of these, the Gaussian constraint thermostat, rescales the velocities
 of atoms at each timestep to achieve a constant system temperature, however
 this algorithm will destroy dynamic correlations very quickly.
 The basic algorithm is detailed below: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{v}(t+\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\leftarrow(2\eta-1)\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)+\eta\Delta t\frac{\underline{f}(t)}{m}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{r}(t+\Delta t)\leftarrow\underline{r}(t)+\Delta t\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\eta=\sqrt{\frac{T_{ext}}{T}}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Where, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset 

 is the temperture at timestep 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 (that is calculated self consistently with three iterations) and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ext}$
\end_inset 

 is the given system temperature or bath temperature.
 
\layout Subsubsection

NVT with Berendsen Thermostat
\layout Standard

The Berendsen thermostat is essentially a cross between the NVE and Gaussian
 algorithms that uses a user defined relaxation constant that determines
 the degree of rescaling of the velocities.
 The Berendsen thermostat can be used to push a system towards a desired
 temperture as oppsed to enforcing it.
 The basic algorithm is detailed bellow:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{v}(t+\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\leftarrow\eta\left(\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)+\Delta t\frac{\underline{f}(t)}{m}\right)\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{r}(t+\Delta t)\leftarrow\underline{r}(t)+\Delta t\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\eta\leftarrow\sqrt{\left[1+\frac{\Delta t}{\tau}\left(\frac{T_{ext}}{T}-1\right)\right]}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 is the user defined time constant in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $ps$
\end_inset 

.
 As with the Gaussian thermostat, the temperature is calcaulted self consistentl
y over three iterations.
 
\layout Subsubsection

NVT with Nose-Hoover Thermostat
\layout Subsubsection

Stochastic Boundary Conditions
\layout Standard

To simulate coupling to a heat bath and to physically allow energy gained
 by the system from a moving tip to be carried off to infinity, all or a
 subset (at the boundaries) of the atoms in a system can be subject to a
 random impulse and frictional force at every timestep, governed by the
 Langevin equation:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial\underline{p}_{i}}{\partial t}=-\frac{\partial U}{\partial\underline{q}_{i}}-\gamma\underline{p}_{i}+F^{+}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

 and the atomic momentums and positions respectively, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset 

 is the total system energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 is the parametric friction coefficient and 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{+}$
\end_inset 

is a Gaussian distributed random force, the size of which is given by the
 second fluctuation-dissipation theorem:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\langle F_{i}^{+}(t_{1})F_{j}^{+}(t_{2})\right\rangle =2\gamma k_{B}T_{ext}\delta_{ij}\delta(t_{1}-t_{2})\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The algorithm used to integrate the equations of motion is the same as the
 Verlet Leapfrog, except that the velocity proportional friction force and
 random impulse is added to the total systematic force prior to the integration.
 The larger the friction coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

, the faster the system will react to a change in temperature and as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\rightarrow0$
\end_inset 

 the system tends to the NVE ensemble.
 The code allows the friction coefficient of each degree of freedom in the
 system to be assigned individually by the user in the input file.
 
\layout Standard

It has been demostrated in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{stochastic-md}

\end_inset 

 that this scheme is only valid when the decay time of the friction coefficient
 is much larger than the time step in the simualtion, i.e.
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta t\ll\frac{1}{\gamma}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The code will not prevent or warn the user from using any value for the
 friction coefficient.
 
\layout Subsubsection

Shells
\layout Standard

The code has the facility to treat shells dynamically by one of two separate
 algorithms, which the user selects.
 The first of these the Dynamical Shell model, first introduced in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{shells-dynamic}

\end_inset 

, each shell is given a small mass and the shell motions are integrated
 along with the atomic cores, in a similar way to a di-atomic molecule.
 This method is computationally cheap, however a smaller timestep must be
 used to allow the high frequency core-shell oscillations to be integrated
 accurately.
 Also over long time periods, kinetic energy unphysically leaks in to the
 core-shell degree of freedom, although the program calculates the core-shell
 temperature and so this can be monitored.
 
\layout Standard

The second algorithm, first introduced in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{shell-relax}

\end_inset 

, relaxes the zero-mass shells at each timestep by minimising the system
 energy with respect to shell positions.
 The shells are then removed for the integration, wile the cores are still
 subject the the shell systematic force.
 This algothim is more physical and accurate than the first, however it
 is much more computationally expensive, since a minimisation must take
 place at every timestep.
 
\layout Standard

At the present time these dynamical shell models have only been impemented
 in the NVE ensemble.
 
\layout Section

Installation
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom bigskip 
The code should be in the form of a zipped tarball, such as 
\family typewriter 
scifi_3.2.tgz
\family default 
.
 Assuming this then type:
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom bigskip 

\family typewriter 
tar -zxvf scifi_3.2.tgz
\layout Standard
\noindent 
this will extract all the necessary files, including directories 
\family typewriter 
SHELLM 
\family default 
(the main code) and
\family typewriter 
 IMAGE
\family default 
 (the image part of the code), a directory 
\family typewriter 
examples
\family default 
 containing three example input files and the corresponding output files.
 
\layout Standard

To compile the program, a 
\family typewriter 
Makefile
\family default 
 in either of the directories 
\family typewriter 
SHELLM
\family default 
 and
\family typewriter 
 IMAGE,
\family default 
 should be edited to include the command of your Fortran 77 or Fortran 90
 compiler (g77 is default), along with any compiler options (-o (optimised)
 is default).
 
\layout Standard

The code can be compiled into either a serial execultable or a MPICH parallel
 version, via the 
\family typewriter 
cpp
\family default 
 precompiler.
 To compile a parallel version, the 
\family typewriter 
MPIFLAG = -DMPI 
\family default 
must be added to the 
\family typewriter 
Makefile
\family default 
, as well as the MPICH flags to your compiler and the path of your 
\family typewriter 
mpich.h
\family default 
 header file.
 
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom smallskip 
To compile the code, type
\family typewriter 
 
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom smallskip 

\family typewriter 
make
\family default 
 
\layout Standard
\noindent 
in either of the two directories; this will produce the executables
\family typewriter 
 shellm
\family default 
 and 
\family typewriter 
image
\family default 
, respectively.
 Make sure that you can access to the two executables, i.e.
 that the directories are included in the 
\family typewriter 
$path
\family default 
 variable.
 
\layout Standard

You can now run the code (see below how).
 Make sure that you can reproduce the output from the the example inputs
 provided in the 
\family typewriter 
examples
\family default 
 directory (section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::Example-Inputs}

\end_inset 

).
