Constraints Box
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{Sec::constraint-box}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom smallskip 

\series bold 
\emph on 
Box Keyword
\series default 
\emph default 
: 
\family typewriter 
.<Constraints>
\layout Standard

See the main points behind the constrained minimisations in section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::constrains-theory}

\end_inset 

.
 Number of constrains is limited to 
\family typewriter 
N0CNSTR
\family default 
 in 
\family typewriter 
param.inc
\family default 
 file.
 Constraints are specified one per line.
 
\layout Itemize

The format for linear constraints is: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{LINR}\,\, I_{1}\,\, C_{1}\,\, I_{2}\,\, C_{2}\,\,\,\cdots\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset 

, etc.
 are coordinate indicators containing atomic number and a letter 
\family typewriter 
x
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
y
\family default 
 or 
\family typewriter 
z
\family default 
, attached from the right.
 The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset 

, etc.
 are associated with the corresponding atomic coordinates and corresponds
 to Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Constraines-view}

\end_inset 

).
 For instance, the condition 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{LINR}\,\,11x\,\,1.0\,\,12x\,\,-1.0\,\,9z\,\,2.0\]

\end_inset 

is equivalent to the following linear constraint: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x_{11}-x_{12}+2z_{9}=0\]

\end_inset 

Note that the first coordinate is used as the redundand one.
 In the example above this will be 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{11}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Itemize

The format for the constraint in which the distance between two atoms in
 kept constant is: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{D}\_1x\,\,\, N_{1}\,\,\, N_{2}\,\, d\,\,\pm\]

\end_inset 

where 
\family typewriter 
D_1x
\family default 
 is the keyword, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}$
\end_inset 

 - atomic numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

 - the distance (in 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset 

 is the sign (either 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset 

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 coordinate of atom 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset 

 is considered as redundand.
\layout Itemize

The format for the constraint in which the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 between three atoms in kept constant is (to be fully implemented when necessary
): 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{C}\_1x\,\,\, N_{1}\,\,\, N_{2}\,\, N_{3}\,\,\alpha\,\,\,\pm\]

\end_inset 

where 
\family typewriter 
C_1x
\family default 
 is the keyword, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{3}$
\end_inset 

 - atomic numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 - the angle (in degrees) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset 

 is the sign (either 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset 

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 coordinate of atom 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset 

 is considered as redundand.
\layout Itemize

The format of the constraint in which the angle between two atoms and the
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 axis is kept, is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{A}\_1x\,\,\, N_{1}\,\,\, N_{2}\,\,\alpha\,\,\pm\]

\end_inset 

where 
\family typewriter 
A_1x
\family default 
 is the keyword, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}$
\end_inset 

 - atomic numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 - the angle (in degrees) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset 

 is the sign (either 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset 

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 coordinate of atom 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset 

 is considered as redundand.
\layout Subsection

Quantum cluster
\layout Standard

The code can be run alongside the GAUSSIAN code in which case atoms in the
 system associated with the quantum cluster need to be identified.
 This option works presently only with pairwise interatomic interactions.
 To specify atoms belonging to the quantum cluster (QC) put the @ character
 immediately after the atomic symbol, e.g.
 :
\layout Standard

\SpecialChar ~

\layout Standard

Cr@ x y z (iRx iRy iRz)
\layout Standard

\SpecialChar ~

\layout Standard
\align left 
If there are quantum cluster atoms in the system, the total energy will
 have a different meaning as the self-energy of the nvironment and its short-ran
ge interaction with the atoms of the QC.
 
\layout Standard

This option was originally designed to calculate the electronic structure
 of the Cr
\begin_inset Formula $^{3+}$
\end_inset 

 defect in MgO taking into account all polarisation charges in the junction
 as obtained by a non-selfconsistent run of the SCI-FI code.
\layout Standard

Please, contact the present authors if interested in knowing this in more
 detail!
\layout Section

Output
\layout Subsection

Standard Output
\layout Standard

The output to the screen will tell you the main parameters for your calculation
 and will also warn you of any obvious inconsistencies that the program
 is trying to compensate for.
 If there are any major problems with the input the program will exit with
 a fatal error and a message explaining the nature of the error.
\layout Subsection

Output File
\layout Standard

Every run will produce an output file called 
\family typewriter 
name.OUT
\family default 
, this will contain detailed information (depending on the printing parameter)
 about your system and the calculations run on it.
 The first stage of the output file will give all the input parameters as
 recognized by the program followed by some basic information about your
 system derived from those parameters.
 This is the first place to check for consistency, make sure that the output
 is consistent with the system you intended in your input.
 The rest of the output file will detail the process of the calculations,
 including a display of the total energy and all forces (and the source
 of those forces) on the atoms at each relaxation iteration.
 If an energy minimisation calculation is being performed, then at the end
 of the file the total force on the tip (if there was one) will be displayed
 along with a total force breakdown.
 
\layout Subsection

Configuration Files
\layout Standard

If a minimisation calculation is being performed and the 
\series bold 
xyz
\series default 
 option is present in the Toleranc box, then the program will produce two
 
\family typewriter 
.xyz 
\family default 
format files: 
\family typewriter 
name_core.xyz
\family default 
 and 
\family typewriter 
name_shell.xyz
\family default 
, containing the final relaxed coordinates of the cores and shells in the
 system correspondingly.
 If a scan is performed using the energy minimisation method (i.e.
 the TipDynamics box is present), the two files will contain coordinates
 of cores and shells at every point at the tip path one after another.
\layout Subsection

Statistics File
\layout Standard

If a Molecular Dynamics simulation is being performed, the run will produce
 a file with thermodynamic data at intervals set with the 
\series bold 
statistics
\series default 
 variable, with the filename 
\family typewriter 
name.STS
\family default 
.
 This file constists of a line for every interval, split into six columns
 that give: timestep, total system energy, potential energy, kinetic energy,
 temperature and shell temperature.
 
\layout Standard

The same file is also produced during a scan made using options in the TipDynami
cs box.
 If only energy minimisation is performed (the box MDcontrol is absent)
 and the tip is allowed to move (the TipDynamics box is present), the file
 will contain only total energies of the system at every scan point.
\layout Subsection

Trajectory File
\layout Standard

An MD run will produce a trajectory file named 
\family typewriter 
name.TRJ
\family default 
 of the format and interval specified in the MDcontrol box.
 This file contains the atomic coordinates of the system at each interval.
 
\layout Subsection

Tip Force Files
\layout Standard

If a Molecular Dynamics simulation is being peformed, then the run will
 produce a file with the total z-component of the force on the tip at every
 timestep called 
\family typewriter 
name.TFZ
\family default 
.
 If the the 
\series bold 
do_lat
\series default 
 flag is used in the MDcontrol box, then x- and y-components of the total
 force on the tip at every timestep will be written to the files 
\family typewriter 
name.TFX
\family default 
 and 
\family typewriter 
name.TFY
\family default 
 respectively.
 
\layout Standard

The same files are produced during a scan (i.e.
 when the TipDynamics box is present) if only energy minimisation is performed
 (the box MDcontrol is absent).
\layout Subsection

Output from 
\family typewriter 
image
\layout Standard

If the image input box is activated correctly then the image interaction
 in your system will be calculated and several other output files will be
 produced.
 In general it is not necessary to look at these, but they are useful for
 detailed analysis of the image force and also for finding the source of
 any strange behaviour in the calculations.
 The possible files produced are as follows:
\layout Itemize


\emph on 
charges.out
\emph default 
 - which contains the position (in a.u.) and charge of every image charge
 created (if 
\series bold 
qwrite
\series default 
 is on).
\layout Itemize


\emph on 
forces.out
\emph default 
 - which contains the image force on every atom (excluding the 
\series bold 
frozen-tip
\series default 
 atoms) and the total image force.
\layout Itemize


\emph on 
image.out
\emph default 
 - which contains an output of the parameters used in calculating the image
 force.
\layout Itemize


\emph on 
out
\emph default 
 - standard output from calculating image force on atoms.
\layout Itemize


\emph on 
outf 
\emph default 
- standard output from calculating the image force on the tip.
\layout Itemize


\emph on 
potent.out
\emph default 
 - which contains the image potential on all atoms in the system and the
 image energy.
